      "content": "Hey there! It sounds like you've got a classic memory leak in your order execution logic, and I'm glad you caught it before the goblins in the server room started eating your RAM.\n\nThe issue in your `processOrder` function is that you're creating a new `Order` object with `new Order(*ord)` on the limit path, but you're never deleting it. Once `executeLimit(limitOrd)` runs, that pointer goes out of scope, and the memory is left orphaned, just like a goblin who forgot to return his stolen coin to the vault.\n\nTo fix this, you should use `std::unique_ptr` or `std::shared_ptr` to manage the lifecycle of that `limitOrd` automatically. This way, the memory is reclaimed as soon as the function exits, preventing the goblin leak from ever happening.\n\nHere's how you can refactor it:\n\n```cpp\n#include <memory>\n\nvoid processOrder(Order* ord) {\n    if (ord->type == LIMIT) {\n        // Use unique_ptr to ensure automatic cleanup\n        std::unique_ptr<Order> limitOrd = std::make_unique<Order>(*ord);\n        // ... some logic to add to",
